            <td>5
            <td>Version Control
            <td>Version control is the process of managing modifications made to source code and documents.
              It helps the developer team roll back to previous versions, making project management and monitoring more efficient.
              
            <td>Adelina Karpenkova. (August 12, 2022). Understanding Version Control: A Guide for DevOps. Scribehow. https://scribehow.com/library/what-is-version-control
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>6
            <td>Automation
            <td>Automation refers to the use of automated tools and scripts to replace humans in performing repetitive tasks. This approach is an excellent means of improving efficiency while minimizing human involvement.
            <td>Editorial Staff. ( August 12, 2022). IT Automation Explained. Advsyscon. https://www.advsyscon.com/blog/it-automation-explained/
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>7
            <td>Infrastructure as Code (IaC)
            <td>The practice of managing and provisioning infrastructure resources using programmable scripts and tools. This practice also includes version control and helps to ensure stable software delivery.
            <td>Souza, I. S. e., Franco, D. P., & Silva, J. P. S. G. (2023). Infrastructure as Code as a Foundational Technique for Increasing the DevOps Maturity Level: Two Case Studies. IEEE Software, Software, IEEE, IEEE Softw, 40(1), 63–68. https://doi.org/10.1109/MS.2022.3213228
          </tr>
